EDA¶

By looking all the variables and ther details it was chosen to split the EDA part in 2 approaches:

  • First will be work with variables related to customer with the goal to define a customer profile
  • Second will be work with variables related to the business with the goal to increase awareness about the strenghts and weekness of the business based on the approach methodology used toward the customers.

#While doing uni-variate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency 
# and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical 
# variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots 
# and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    sns.set(font_scale=2) # setting the font scale  of the seaborn
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='red') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins) if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='g', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.
def bar_perc(plot, feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: 1-d categorical feature array
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 20) # annotate the percantage

Observations Customer Profile

  • Salaried representing the majority of customers with second place for small business owners. Both classes representating 91% of customers
  • Gender male representing 59.7% of customers.
  • 47.9% of customers are married with the remaining almost equally split in divorced, single and unmarried.
  • Executives and Managers represents 71.1% of customers with a third position for Senior Managers with 15.9%.
  • Prefered destinations are cities Tier 1 category.
  • 3 stars properties score represents 62% of choices.

Business Summary

  • Product Pitched were concentraded on Basic and Deluxe packages representing 71.8%. The third was the standard package with 15.9%. -71% of the type of contact was self enquiry with the remaining 29% belonging to customers invited by sales team.

Observations

  • Positive correlated variables are below sorted by most correlated variables to lowest ones:
    • Number of Person visited by Number of Children Visited. Makes sense since this variable might have some overlap.
    • Age by income which intuitivelly makes sense.
    • Number of Person visited is correlated to number of followups.
    • Passport is correlated to whether or not people bought our offered packages.
  • Negative correlated variables are below sorted by most correlated variables to lowest ones:
    • Product taken by Montly Income, in other words when Monthly Income increases Product Taken decrease.
    • Age by Product taken, when ages increases Product Taken decrease.

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predict a customer will purchase a turism package but customer does NOT purchase it. (FP)
  2. Predict a customer will not purchase a turism package but customer DOES purchase it. (FN)

Which case is more important?¶

  1. Predict a customer will purchase a turism package but customer does NOT purchase it is more important for this study since the main goal is to make marketing expenditure more efficient and by wrongly predict a customer would be a package, sales / marketing team would have made calls (time consuming) to follow-up sales process when they could be focused on customers who would actually purchase the packages.

How to to make marketing expenditure more efficient i.e need to reduce False Positive?¶

  • Company wants Precision to be maximized, greater the Precision higher the chances of minimizing false positives. Hence, the focus should be on increasing Precision or minimizing the false positive or in other words identifying the true negatives so that the company can spend their resources more efficiently.

Let's define function to provide metric scores(accuracy) on train and test set and a function to show confusion matrix so that we do not have use the same code repetitively while evaluating models.

In [47]:
##  Function to calculate accuracy score
def get_accuracy_score(model,flag=True):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    c = [] # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    train_acc = model.score(X_train,y_train)
    test_acc = model.score(X_test,y_test)
    c.append(train_acc) # adding train accuracy to list
    c.append(test_acc) # adding test accuracy to list
    if flag == True: # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed
        print("Accuracy on training set : ",model.score(X_train,y_train))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ",model.score(X_test,y_test))
    
    return c # returning the list with train and test scores
In [48]:
##  Function to calculate precision score
def get_precision_score(model,flag=True):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    b = []  # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test,pred_test)
    b.append(train_precision) # adding train precision to list
    b.append(test_precision) # adding test precision to list
    if flag == True: # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed
        print("Precision on training set : ",metrics.precision_score(y_train,pred_train))
        print("Precision on test set : ",metrics.precision_score(y_test,pred_test))

    return b # returning the list with train and test scores
In [49]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

Conclusion¶

Most important features to predict wheather a customer will purchase the offered packages are:

Customer profile:¶

  • Monthly Income
  • Age
  • Passport
  • Designation = Executive

Business Awareness:¶

  • Duration of the pitch
  • Number of follow ups
  • City Tier (3)
  • Pitch Satisfaction Score
